Eric Postpischil (edp@math.zk3.dec.com) wrote:
: In article <gradyCt5qsA.G0F@netcom.com>, grady@netcom.com (Grady Ward) writes:

: >The fact Phil claims to have produced PGP 1.0, has a PGP key in the key
: >database, and has been known to use PGP for messages all are evidence
: >that he has infringed on the RSA patent.

: No, they are not.  Public Key Partners has a publicly-stated policy of
: allowing use of the RSA algorithm for personal, intellectual, and
: educational reasons.  Writing PGP, generating and distributing a key,
: and using PGP for messages are consistent with personal, intellectual,
: and educational use.

If this is true, then it seems that *all* version of PGP were non-infringing.
But Jim Bidzos said that he would grant a license to PGP (<2.4 anyway)
So -- something is not quite right.


